1 Problem 1: Hypothesis Testing for \(\mu_1-\mu_2\) with two independent samples

Several neurosurgeons wanted to determine whether a dynamic system (Z-plate) reduced operative time relative to a static system (ALPS plate). The operative times, in minutes, for 14 dynamic replications of the operation and 6 static replications were obtained and are given below. The neurosurgeons believe the collection of all operative times with either device would be roughly normally distributed. Test the claim at 0.05 significant level using the steps given in the lecture.

\[\begin{align} Dynamic:&\; 370, 360, 510, 445, 295, 315, 490, 345, 450, 505, 335, 280, 325, 500\\ Static:&\; 430, 445, 455, 455, 490, 535\\ \end{align}\]

  1. State null and alternative hypotheses.

  2. Describe the data

    A. Compute a summary statistic (n, mean, sd, min, and max) for both groups. Interpret your findings.

    B. Present a Graph comparison of the variables. Interpret your findings.

  3. Check assumptions

    A. Simple random sampling

    B. Independence

    C. Normality

    D. Homogeneity of variance

  4. Perform the appropriated Test and make a decision: Use the appropriated R function based on your assumptions. Also, use the bootstrap code provided in the lecture to perform a bootstrap hypothesis test of the hypotheses: use the p-value method and confidence interval method.

  5. Write your conclusions

2 Step 1. State null and alternative hypotheses

  1. Claim: âTo determine whether a dynamic system (Z-plate) reduced operative time relative to a static system (ALPS plate).â

  2. The random variables involved in the claim are:

\[\begin{align} X_{D}:&\; \textrm{The operative time under a dynamic system (Z-plate).}\\ X_{S}:&\; \textrm{The operative time under the static system (ALPS plate).}\\ X_{D}-X_{S}:&\; \textrm{The mean difference in operative time between a dynamic system and a static system.} \end{align}\]

Notice that these variables are quantitative continuous.

  1. The parameter of interest

We will use the notation.

  • \(\mu_{D} =\) The mean operative time under a dynamic system (Z-plate).

  • \(\mu_{S} =\) The mean operative time under the static system (ALPS plate).

The parameters are

\[\begin{align} \textrm{Variable}\; X_{D}:&\; \textrm{The parameter is}\; \mu_{D} \\ \textrm{Variable}\; X_{S}:&\; \textrm{The parameter is}\; \mu_{S} \\ \textrm{Variable}\;X_{D}-X_{S}:&\; \textrm{the parameter is}\; \mu_{S} - \mu_{\textrm{S}} \end{align}\]

  1. The claim in symbolic form is: \(\mu_{D} < \mu_{S}\)

  2. The claim in symbolic form that must be opposite to the original claim is: \(\mu_{D} \geq \mu_{S}\) or \(\mu_{D} = \mu_{S}\)

  3. The null hypothesis and alternative hypotheses \[ \bbox[#ffcc99,20px,border:10px ligth red] { H_{0}: \mu_{\textrm{D}} = \mu_{S} \;\;\textrm{vs}\;\;H_{A}: \mu_{D} < \mu_{S} } \]

Or, equivalently:

\[ \bbox[#ffcc99,20px,border:10px ligth red] { H_{0}: \mu_{D} - \mu_{S} = 0 \;\;vs\;\;H_{A}: \mu_{D} - \mu_{S} < 0 } \]

5 Step 3. Check assumptions

Now that we have explored the data, we check the assumptions.

  • Are the two samples simple random samples?

Yes. We know it from the data set information. We have no paired data.

  • Do the two populations are independent?

We have a different group of data.

  • Do the two random samples come from a population with normals distributions?
par(mfrow=c(2,1))

qqnorm(Dynamic,col="aquamarine3",pch=16,cex=1.4,main = "Q-Q Plot Static")
qqline(Dynamic,col="blue")

qqnorm(Static,col="firebrick3",pch=16,cex=1.4,main = "Q-Q Plot Dynamic")
qqline(Static,col="blue")

The Q-Q plot is not great, but based on the neurosurgeons believe that the collection of all operative times with either device would be roughly normally distributed, we will say that the population normality assumption is reasonably met.

  • Do the two samples come from populations with equal variances?

The equal variances assumption does not seem to be met because there appears to be more spread in the Dynamics group. Checking our guideline, \(\frac{s_{1}}{s_{2}} = \frac{84.75}{38.17} =38.17\). Then the equality of variance it is not satisfied since it is not true that \(0.5\leq\frac{s_1}{s_2}\leq2\).

5.1 Step 4. Perform the appropriate test statistic

Since we have not equal variances, we will use Welchâs t-test. The statistic is:

\[ T = \dfrac{\bar{X}_{D} - \bar{X}_{S} - 0}{\sqrt{\dfrac{S^{2}_{D}}{n_{D}} + \dfrac{S^{2}_{S}}{n_{S}}}}\;;\;\; \textrm{with}\;\; df = \dfrac{\left(\frac{S^{2}_{D}}{n_{D}} + \dfrac{S^{2}_{S}}{n_{S}}\right)^{2}}{\dfrac{(S^{2}_{D}/n_{D})^2}{n_{D}-1} + \dfrac{(S^{2}_{S}/n_{S})^2}{n_{S}-1}} \]

The observed statistics using R by hand is

t.obs<-(mean(Dynamic)-mean(Static))/sqrt((var(Dynamic)/length(Dynamic))+(var(Static)/length(Static)))
t.obs
## [1] -2.68042

\[ t_{obs} = \dfrac{394.64 - 468.33 - 0}{\sqrt{\dfrac{7182.55}{14} + \dfrac{1456.67}{6}}}=-2.68\;;\;\; \textrm{with}\;\; df = \frac{\left(\frac{7182.55}{14} + \frac{1456.67}{6}\right)^{2}}{\frac{(84.75/14)^2}{14-1} + \frac{(38.17/6)^2}{6-1}} = 17.83. \]

6 Methods to take a decision

6.1 Method 1: Rejection region

Since \(\alpha= 0.05\) and df=17.83. We put \(0.025\) in the left and right tails of the t distribution. The rejection region is defined by:

\[ \bbox[#ffcc99,20px,border:10px ligth red] { \textrm{Reject}\;H_0:\;T>t_{17.83,0.975}\;\;\textrm{or}\;\;T<t_{17.83,0.025} } \]

Where \(t_{17.83,0.025}\) and \(t_{17.83,0.975}\) are the critical values. We can compute them using R:

t.1<-qt(0.025, df=df) 
t.1
## [1] -2.102339
t.2<-qt(0.975, df=df) 
t.2
## [1] 2.102339

The critical values are \(t_{(17.83,0.025)} = -2.1\) and \(t_{(17.83,0.975)} = 2.1\).

Then the rejection region is

\[ \bbox[#ffcc99,20px,border:10px ligth red] { \textrm{Reject}\; H_0\; \textrm{if:}\; T>2.1 \;\;\textrm{or}\;\; T<-2.1 } \]

  • Since the t.obs=\(-2.68\) do fall into the rejection region, we reject the null hypothesis.

6.2 Method 2: P-value

In R:

p.value<-pt(q=t.obs,df=df)
p.value
## [1] 0.007679065

It was calculated as

\[\textrm{p-value}=P(T_{17.83}<-2.68)=0.0076791.\]

  • Since the p-value is relatively small, \(\textrm{p-value}=0.0076791<0.05\), we reject the nul hypothesis \(H_0:\mu_D-\mu_S=0\).

7 Method 3: Confidence interval.

Again we can make a confidence interval. The form is again the same, but the estimated standard error of the estimate changes. Theinterval estimator is given by

\[\bar{X}_{D} - \bar{X}_{S} \pm t_{df, \alpha/2} * \sqrt{\frac{S^{2}_{D}}{n_{D}} + \frac{S^{2}_{D}}{n_{D}}}\]

  • Computation in R by steps
dif.mean<-mean(Dynamic)-mean(Static)
dif.mean
## [1] -73.69048
var<-((sd(Dynamic)^2)/length(Dynamic)+(sd(Static)^2)/length(Static))
var
## [1] 755.8174
se<-sqrt(var)
se
## [1] 27.49213
t=qt(p=alpha2, df=df) 

t
## [1] 2.102339
E= t*se
E
## [1] 57.79779
ci.lower=dif.mean-E
ci.lower
## [1] -131.4883
ci.upper=dif.mean+E
ci.upper
## [1] -15.89269
  • Thus an approximate \(95\%\) confidence interval for \(\mu_{\textrm{D}} -\mu_{\textrm{S}}\) would be \((-131.49,-15.89)\) or \[-131.49<\;\;\mu_{\textrm{D}} - \mu_{\textrm{S}}< -15.89.\]

Since the interval does not cover zero, we would reject the null hypothesis that the difference is zero, just as we concluded using the test.

7.1 In R using the t.test() function

t.test(Dynamic, Static, paired=FALSE, var.equal=FALSE, conf.level=.95, alternative="less")
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  Dynamic and Static
## t = -2.6804, df = 17.832, p-value = 0.007679
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is less than 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##       -Inf -25.99307
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##  394.6429  468.3333

Where

  1. alternative = "less" since the alternative hypothesis is \((H_0:\mu_{D}-\mu_{S}< 0)\).

  2. mu = 0 since the value under the null hypothesis is 0 \((H_0:\mu_{D}-\mu_{S}=0)\).

  3. paired = FALSE since the two populations are independent.

  4. var.equal = FALSE since the two populations variance is different.

  5. conf.level = 0.95 since the level of significance is \(\alpha=0.05\).

  • P-value: The p-value is \(0.0076791\) which is less than \(\alpha=0.05\). Thus, we have sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis at the \(\alpha=0.05\) level.

  • Confidence interval: The \(95\%\) one-sided confidence interval for the true difference in operating time between the dynamic and static system is \((-\infty{}, -25.99)\) minutes. Since this interval does not include \(0\) as a likely value for the true difference in means, we have evidence to reject the null hypothesis at the \(\alpha=0.05\) level.

7.2 Using Bootstrap

boottwo<-function(dat1, dat2, nboot) {
 
    bootstat<-NULL

    for(i in 1:nboot) {
        truediff<-mean(dat1) - mean(dat2)
        n1<-length(dat1)
        n2<-length(dat2)
        samp1<-sample(dat1, size = n1, replace = T)
        samp2<-sample(dat2, size = n2, replace = T)
        bootmean1<-mean(samp1)
        bootmean2<-mean(samp2)
        bootvar1<-var(samp1)
        bootvar2<-var(samp2)
        bootstat[i]<-(bootmean1 - bootmean2 - truediff)/sqrt((bootvar1/n1) + (bootvar2/n2))
}

    return(bootstat)
}
  • Run the bootstrap function boottwo() for cricket data
set.seed(1)
cricketboot<-boottwo(Dynamic, Static, 5000) # generate 5000 simulated values of the Welch's T-test
hist(cricketboot,col="aquamarine3",xlab="t hats")

  • Compute the observed t-test
mDynamic<-mean(Dynamic)
vDynamic<-var(Dynamic)
nDynamic<-length(Dynamic)
mStatic<-mean(Static)
vStatic<-var(Static)
nStatic<-length(Static)
tobs<-(mDynamic - mStatic)/sqrt(vDynamic/nDynamic + vStatic/nStatic) # Observed t value
tobs
## [1] -2.68042
  • Find p-value for two-sided
mlo<-sum(cricketboot <= -abs(tobs))
mlo
## [1] 33
pval<-mlo/5000
pval
## [1] 0.0066

We found 33 \(\hat{t}\) values less than -2.68, for a p-value of \(0.0066 < 0.05\). Thus, we reject the null hypothesis.

7.3 Step 5. State the conclusion and interpret the decision

There is sufficient statistical evidence to suggest that the mean operative time is lower with the dynamic system.

8 Problem 2

Using the information in problem 1, perform in R a Wilcoxon Rank Sum/Mann-Whitney test for evidence that the population of Dynamic surgical times is shifted left of the Static surgical times. Report the observed Test Statistic, p-value, and conclusions.

8.1 Step 1. State null and alternative hypotheses

The Hypotheses are in terms of the two population distributions (not their means)

\[\begin{align} H_0:&\; \textrm{The distributions of the operation time for both groups: dynamic and static are identical}\\ H_A:&\;\textrm{The distributions of the two groups: dynamic and static have the same shape, but one is shifted relative to the other} \end{align}\]

8.1.1 Step 2. Data exploration

par(mfrow=c(2,1))

hist(Dynamic,col="aquamarine3",xlim = c(280.0,535.0),xlab="Operating Time with the Dynamic System(minutes)")
hist(Static,col="firebrick3",xlim = c(280.0,535.0),xlab="Operating Time with the Statics System(minutes)")

8.2 Step 3. Check assumptions

  • Note that we are talking about distributions.
  1. Are there independence between and within groups?

From the dataâs nature, the data are not paired, the independence between groups (Dynamic and Static) is validated.

  1. Do the two groups (fed and starved) have the same shape?

In our example, the shapes of the histograms do not look all that similar. However, we need to keep in mind that 4 or 16 data points are not very many when establishing the shape of the distribution. For now, we will tentatively assume that they are close enough.

  • But if there is any concern about this assumption, we would need to use a different method. For example, the bootstrap or permutation test, neither of which makes any assumption about the distributions shapes.

8.3 Step 4. Perform the appropriate test statistic and take the decision

wilcox.test(Dynamic, Static, alternative="less",conf.level = 0.95)
## Warning in wilcox.test.default(Dynamic, Static, alternative = "less", conf.level
## = 0.95): cannot compute exact p-value with ties
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  Dynamic and Static
## W = 23, p-value = 0.06331
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is less than 0

The observed statistic is W=23 and the p-value=0.06331. We reject the null hypothesis. We have much lower evidence against the null than when using the t-test.

8.4 Step 5. State the conclusion and interpret the decision

  • So we can conclude based on this data that the distributions of the two groups: dynamic and static, have the same shape, but one is shifted relative to the other. The dynamic is shifted to the left compared to the static.
